    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="754"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d754">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.932/17</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2431</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-13">April 13,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received May 3.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to my despatch no. 2411 of April
                    8th, on the subject of the right of aliens to acquire and hold land in China, I
                    have now the honor to enclose copy of a memorandum of conversation <pb
                        facs="1029" n="1015" xml:id="pg_1015"/> with the Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs together with copy of a memorandum handed me by the latter outlining the
                    treaty provisions and provisions of Chinese law on foreign landholding in
                        China.<note n="16" xml:id="d754fn16">Enclosures not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The enclosures contribute nothing further to the general subject as discussed in
                    despatch no. 2411, but it will be of interest to note the remark to me by the
                    Foreign Minister that China is disposed to grant to Americans the same rights
                    granted to other foreign nationals and that China will be prepared to concede to
                    Americans the right to acquire and hold real property in China.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
